{"title_page": "Shinkansen Relay", "text_new": "{{italictitle}}\n{{Infobox rail service\n| name        = ''Shinkansen Relay''\n| image       = 185-200 Shinkansen Relay Omiya 1982.jpg\n| image_width = 300px\n| caption     = 185-200 series ''Shinkansen Relay'' at \u014cmiya Station, 1982\n| type        = [[Limited express]]\n| status      = \n| locale      = [[T\u014dhoku Main Line]]\n| predecessor = \n| first       = June 1982\n| last        = 13 March 1985\n| successor   = \n| operator    = \n| formeroperator= [[JNR]]\n| ridership   = \n| start       = {{STN|Ueno}}\n| stops       = Non-stop\n| end         = {{STN|\u014cmiya|Saitama}}\n| distance    = {{Convert|26.7|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| journeytime = 26 minutes\n| frequency   = Every 30 minutes\n| trainnumber = \n| class       = \n| access      = \n| seating     = \n| catering    = \n| stock       = [[185 series#185-200 series|185-200 series]] EMUs\n| gauge       = {{RailGauge|1067mm}}\n| el          = 1,500 V DC overhead\n| speed       = \n| owners      = \n| routenumber =\n| map         = \n| map_state   = \n}}\n\nThe {{Nihongo|'''''Shinkansen Relay'''''|\u65b0\u5e79\u7dda\u30ea\u30ec\u30fc\u53f7}} was a train service operated by [[Japanese National Railways]] (JNR) in Japan between 1982 and 1985.<ref name=\"navi2004\">{{cite book | script-title=ja: \u65b0\u5e79\u7dda\uff2e\uff21\uff36\uff29 |trans-title=Shinkansen Navi| publisher = Ikaros Publishing | date = July 2004 | location = Japan | page = | isbn = 4-87149-562-0}}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[Tohoku Shinkansen]] was opened in June 1982, the planned section between {{STN|Ueno}} in Tokyo and {{STN|\u014cmiya|Saitama}} was not complete, with shinkansen services starting and terminating at \u014cmiya Station. The ''Shinkansen Relay'' was therefore provided to shuttle passengers between Ueno and \u014cmiya via the [[narrow gauge]] [[Tohoku Main Line]]. Initially, 13 [[Railroad direction|down]] and 14 up services operated daily, taking 26 minutes for the non-stop journey. From November 1982, the frequency was increased to 28 down and 29 up services daily, running at 30-minute intervals during the daytime off-peak.<ref name=\"yamanouchi2002\"/> Services consisted of pairs of 7-car [[185 series#185-200 series|185-200 series]] EMUs, providing a total seating capacity of 848. One ''Shinkansen Relay'' service served a pair of [[Tohoku Shinkansen]] and [[Joetsu Shinkansen]] services.<ref name=\"navi2004\"/> Express [[455 series]] and suburban [[115 series]] EMUs were also used on some trains.<ref name=\"yamanouchi2002\">{{cite book| last = Yamanouchi | first = Sh\u016bichir\u014d | script-title=ja: \u6771\u5317\u30fb\u4e0a\u8d8a\u65b0\u5e79\u7dda |trans-title=T\u014dhoku & J\u014detsu Shinkansen| publisher = JTB Can Books | date = 2002 | location = Tokyo, Japan | page = | isbn = 4-533-04513-8}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Shinkansen Relay'' service ended on 13 March 1985, the day before the [[Tohoku Shinkansen]] opened between Ueno and \u014cmiya. The 185-200 series EMUs were reassigned for use on other [[Limited express]] services such as the ''[[Kusatsu (train)|Kusatsu]]''.<ref name=\"navi2004\"/>\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Rapid ''Shinkansen Relay'' (1998&ndash;2001)==\n[[File:201 165 Shinkansen Relay Hachioji 20010801.jpg|thumb|165 series EMU on a ''Shinkansen Relay'' rapid service at Hachi\u014dji Station, August 2001]]\nThe ''Shinkansen Relay'' name was reintroduced between 1998 and 2001 for morning and evening limited-stop {{Nihongo|\"Rapid\"|\u5feb\u901f|kaisoku}} services between {{STN|Hachi\u014dji}} and {{STN|\u014cmiya|Saitama}} via the [[Musashino Line]] to provide connections to northbound shinkansen services for passengers originating from the [[Ch\u016b\u014d Line (Rapid)]] area. Services were introduced in 1997 as the ''Komachi Relay'' before becoming the ''Shinkansen Relay'', and were formed of 6-car [[165 series|165]] and [[169 series]] EMU formations. The services were renamed ''[[Musashino (train)|Musashino]]'' from 2001.\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Rapid ''Shinkansen Relay'' (April 2011)==\n[[File:Shinkansen Relay 583 in Sendai 2011.JPG|thumb|583 series EMU on a ''Shinkansen Relay'' rapid service at Sendai Station, April 2011]]\nThe ''Shinkansen Relay'' name was again used for a short period from 12 to 24 April 2011 for limited-stop \"Rapid\" services operated between {{STN|Fukushima|Fukushima}} and {{STN|Sendai|Miyagi}} via the [[Tohoku Main Line]] as a substitute for the [[Tohoku Shinkansen]], which was closed over this section following the 11 March [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]]. Trains were operated using [[485 series]], [[583 series]], and [[E721 series]] EMUs, with all seats non-reserved.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.kotsu.co.jp/index.php?cID=1040|script-title= ja:\u300c\u65b0\u5e79\u7dda\u30ea\u30ec\u30fc\u53f7\u300d\u904b\u8ee2\u3000\u6771\u5317\u7dda\u798f\u5cf6\u2015\u4ed9\u53f0\u9593\u3067|trans-title= ''Shinkansen Relay'' operates on Tohoku Line between Fukushima and Sendai|date= 13 April 2011|work= Kotsu Shimbun Online|publisher= Kotsu Shimbunsha|location= Japan|language= Japanese|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130709040717/http://www.kotsu.co.jp/index.php?cID=1040|archivedate= 9 July 2013|accessdate= 16 August 2012|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Shinkansen]]\n[[Category:East Japan Railway Company]]\n[[Category:Named passenger trains of Japan]]\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 1982]]\n", "text_old": "{{italictitle}}\n{{Infobox rail service\n| name        = ''Shinkansen Relay''\n| image       = 185-200 Shinkansen Relay Omiya 1982.jpg\n| image_width = 300px\n| caption     = 185-200 series ''Shinkansen Relay'' at \u014cmiya Station, 1982\n| type        = [[Limited express]]\n| status      = \n| locale      = [[T\u014dhoku Main Line]]\n| predecessor = \n| first       = June 1982\n| last        = 13 March 1985\n| successor   = \n| operator    = \n| formeroperator= [[JNR]]\n| ridership   = \n| start       = {{STN|Ueno}}\n| stops       = Non-stop\n| end         = {{STN|\u014cmiya|Saitama}}\n| distance    = {{Convert|26.7|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| journeytime = 26 minutes\n| frequency   = Every 30 minutes\n| trainnumber = \n| class       = \n| access      = \n| seating     = \n| catering    = \n| stock       = [[185 series#185-200 series|185-200 series]] EMUs\n| gauge       = {{RailGauge|1067mm}}\n| el          = 1,500 V DC overhead\n| speed       = \n| owners      = \n| routenumber =\n| map         = \n| map_state   = \n}}\n\nThe {{Nihongo|'''''Shinkansen Relay'''''|\u65b0\u5e79\u7dda\u30ea\u30ec\u30fc\u53f7}} was a train service operated by [[Japanese National Railways]] (JNR) in Japan between 1982 and 1985.<ref name=\"navi2004\">{{cite book | script-title=ja: \u65b0\u5e79\u7dda\uff2e\uff21\uff36\uff29 |trans-title=Shinkansen Navi| publisher = Ikaros Publishing | date = July 2004 | location = Japan | page = | isbn = 4-87149-562-0}}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[Tohoku Shinkansen]] was opened in June 1982, the planned section between {{STN|Ueno}} in Tokyo and {{STN|\u014cmiya|Saitama}} was not complete, with shinkansen services starting and terminating at \u014cmiya Station. The ''Shinkansen Relay'' was therefore provided to shuttle passengers between Ueno and \u014cmiya via the [[narrow gauge]] [[Tohoku Main Line]]. Initially, 13 [[Railroad direction|down]] and 14 up services operated daily, taking 26 minutes for the non-stop journey. From November 1982, the frequency was increased to 28 down and 29 up services daily, running at 30-minute intervals during the daytime off-peak.<ref name=\"yamanouchi2002\"/> Services consisted of pairs of 7-car [[185 series#185-200 series|185-200 series]] EMUs, providing a total seating capacity of 848. One ''Shinkansen Relay'' service served a pair of [[Tohoku Shinkansen]] and [[Joetsu Shinkansen]] services.<ref name=\"navi2004\"/> Express [[455 series]] and suburban [[115 series]] EMUs were also used on some trains.<ref name=\"yamanouchi2002\">{{cite book| last = Yamanouchi | first = Sh\u016bichir\u014d | script-title=ja: \u6771\u5317\u30fb\u4e0a\u8d8a\u65b0\u5e79\u7dda |trans-title=T\u014dhoku & J\u014detsu Shinkansen| publisher = JTB Can Books | date = 2002 | location = Tokyo, Japan | page = | isbn = 4-533-04513-8}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Shinkansen Relay'' service ended on 13 March 1985, the day before the [[Tohoku Shinkansen]] opened between Ueno and \u014cmiya. The 185-200 series EMUs were reassigned for use on other [[Limited express]] services such as the ''[[Kusatsu (train)|Kusatsu]]''.<ref name=\"navi2004\"/>\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Rapid ''Shinkansen Relay'' (1998&ndash;2001)==\n[[File:201 165 Shinkansen Relay Hachioji 20010801.jpg|thumb|165 series EMU on a ''Shinkansen Relay'' rapid service at Hachi\u014dji Station, August 2001]]\nThe ''Shinkansen Relay'' name was reintroduced between 1998 and 2001 for morning and evening limited-stop {{Nihongo|\"Rapid\"|\u5feb\u901f|kaisoku}} services between {{STN|Hachi\u014dji}} and {{STN|\u014cmiya|Saitama}} via the [[Musashino Line]] to provide connections to northbound shinkansen services for passengers originating from the [[Ch\u016b\u014d Line (Rapid)]] area. Services were introduced in 1997 as the ''Komachi Relay'' before becoming the ''Shinkansen Relay'', and were formed of 6-car [[165 series|165]] and [[169 series]] EMU formations. The services were renamed ''[[Musashino (train)|Musashino]]'' from 2001.\n\n{{-}}\n==Rapid ''Shinkansen Relay'' (April 2011)==\n[[File:Shinkansen Relay 583 in Sendai 2011.JPG|thumb|583 series EMU on a ''Shinkansen Relay'' rapid service at Sendai Station, April 2011]]\nThe ''Shinkansen Relay'' name was again used for a short period from 12 to 24 April 2011 for limited-stop \"Rapid\" services operated between {{STN|Fukushima|Fukushima}} and {{STN|Sendai|Miyagi}} via the [[Tohoku Main Line]] as a substitute for the [[Tohoku Shinkansen]], which was closed over this section following the 11 March [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]]. Trains were operated using [[485 series]], [[583 series]], and [[E721 series]] EMUs, with all seats non-reserved.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.kotsu.co.jp/index.php?cID=1040|script-title= ja:\u300c\u65b0\u5e79\u7dda\u30ea\u30ec\u30fc\u53f7\u300d\u904b\u8ee2\u3000\u6771\u5317\u7dda\u798f\u5cf6\u2015\u4ed9\u53f0\u9593\u3067|trans-title= ''Shinkansen Relay'' operates on Tohoku Line between Fukushima and Sendai|date= 13 April 2011|work= Kotsu Shimbun Online|publisher= Kotsu Shimbunsha|location= Japan|language= Japanese|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130709040717/http://www.kotsu.co.jp/index.php?cID=1040|archivedate= 9 July 2013|accessdate= 16 August 2012|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n[[Category:Shinkansen]]\n[[Category:East Japan Railway Company]]\n[[Category:Named passenger trains of Japan]]\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 1982]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shinkansen_Relay"}
{"title_page": "Daniel Shmedin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Daniel Shmedin\n| image = Shmedin.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1991|5|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Sofia]], [[Bulgaria]]\n| height =\n| currentclub = [[PFC Burgas]]\n| clubnumber = 11\n| position = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1= 2000\u20132010\n| youthclubs1= [[PFC Levski Sofia|Levski Sofia]]\n| years1 = 2010\u20132012 | years2 = 2011 | years3 = 2011 | years4 = 2012\u20132013 | years5 = 2014\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[PFC Levski Sofia|Levski Sofia]] | clubs2 =\u2192 [[PFC Kaliakra Kavarna|Kaliakra Kavarna]] (loan) | clubs3 =\u2192 [[FC Slivnishki geroi|Slivnishki geroi]] (loan) | clubs4 = [[FC Vitosha Bistritsa|Vitosha Bistritsa]] | clubs5 = [[PFC Burgas]]\n| caps1 = 3 | goals1 = 0 | caps2 = 3 | goals2 = 0 | caps3 = 8 | goals3 = 0 | caps4 = ? | goals4 = ? | caps5 = 14 | goals5 = 0\n| nationalyears1=\n| nationalteam1=\n| nationalcaps1= | nationalgoals1 = \n| pcupdate = 1 December 2014\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Shmedin''' ({{lang-bg|\u0414\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043b \u0428\u043c\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d}}; born on 7 May 1991) is a [[Bulgaria]]n [[Association football|footballer]]. He currently plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for [[PFC Burgas]].\n\n==Career==\n===Levski Sofia===\nDaniel Shmedin is a youth product of [[PFC Levski Sofia|Levski Sofia]], having joined their youth system in 2000. He rose through the Levski youth teams, eventually becoming an important player for the reserve team.\n\nAfter some good games for the reserves, Daniel was called up to the senior team on 6 April 2010.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090903010044/http://levski.bg/Levski/cms/info/bg/club/kteam90.html Levski Sofia second team]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shmedin, Daniel}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:First Professional Football League (Bulgaria) players]]\n[[Category:PFC Levski Sofia players]]\n[[Category:PFC Kaliakra Kavarna players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Daniel Shmedin\n| image = Shmedin.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1991|5|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Sofia]], [[Bulgaria]]\n| height =\n| currentclub = [[PFC Burgas]]\n| clubnumber = 11\n| position = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1= 2000\u20132010\n| youthclubs1= [[PFC Levski Sofia|Levski Sofia]]\n| years1 = 2010\u20132012 | years2 = 2011 | years3 = 2011 | years4 = 2012\u20132013 | years5 = 2014\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[PFC Levski Sofia|Levski Sofia]] | clubs2 =\u2192 [[PFC Kaliakra Kavarna|Kaliakra Kavarna]] (loan) | clubs3 =\u2192 [[FC Slivnishki geroi|Slivnishki geroi]] (loan) | clubs4 = [[FC Vitosha Bistritsa|Vitosha Bistritsa]] | clubs5 = [[PFC Burgas]]\n| caps1 = 3 | goals1 = 0 | caps2 = 3 | goals2 = 0 | caps3 = 8 | goals3 = 0 | caps4 = ? | goals4 = ? | caps5 = 14 | goals5 = 0\n| nationalyears1=\n| nationalteam1=\n| nationalcaps1= | nationalgoals1 = \n| pcupdate = 1 December 2014\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Shmedin''' ({{lang-bg|\u0414\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043b \u0428\u043c\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d}}; born on 7 May 1991) is a [[Bulgaria]]n [[Association football|footballer]]. He currently plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for [[PFC Burgas]].\n\n==Career==\n===Levski Sofia===\nDaniel Shmedin is a youth product of [[PFC Levski Sofia|Levski Sofia]], having joined their youth system in 2000. He rose through the Levski youth teams, eventually becoming an important player for the reserve team.\n\nAfter some good games for the reserves, Daniel was called up to the senior team on 6 April 2010.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090903010044/http://levski.bg/Levski/cms/info/bg/club/kteam90.html Levski Sofia second team]\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shmedin, Daniel}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:First Professional Football League (Bulgaria) players]]\n[[Category:PFC Levski Sofia players]]\n[[Category:PFC Kaliakra Kavarna players]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_Shmedin"}
